comments.body:
This kind of fork is something we'd like to avoid if at all possible. It would be much preferable to contribute your changes to the original `LevelDB.jl` package.

@jerryzhenleicai: Can you comment on the maintenance status of `LevelDB.jl`? If you don't have the capacity to maintain the package any longer, maybe you could move it to an organization and add @sadit as a maintainer?

@sadit: Have you previously reached out to @jerryzhenleicai? If so, when? In situations where the original maintainer of a package is completely unreachable over a long period (typically at least three months), there is precedent for a "hard fork". In this case, the package is copied (not moved) to an organization with a new maintainer, and the registry is changed to point to this new repository. But this is not something we would do lightly, and there should be a documented sustained effort to contact @jerryzhenleicai through multiple channels.

In the meantime, I would recommend keeping `LevelDB2` in a LocalRegistry, until we can figure how to contribute these changes back to `LevelDB`.

[noblock]

> Also, @gdkrmr seems to have been a more recent maintainer. At least they registered the 2.1.0 release at #3113. They also seem to be still active on Github, so maybe they can clarify the maintenance status of LevelDB and assist in getting these changes merged or the repo moved.

@goerz  @gdkrmr I apologize for not having the time and capacity to review and accept new contributions to LevelDB except periodically ensuring it's tracking the C++ LevelDB library. IMO LevelDB's API in its current form is at an optimal balance of simplicity and functionality and I do not intend to accept any further PRs except bug fixes. Of course being open source I  do not object to extending or maybe even a hard forking of the project. @gdkrmr  is a significant co-contributor so if @gdkrmr  wants to weigh in on this issue I'd love to hear his opinion too. 

[noblock]

Alright, then my vote is to just let `LevelDB2` merge.

@gdkrmr @jerryzhenleicai Can you edit your comments to contain `[noblock]`?

[noblock]
